Frogs and all other living tetrapods have a rod @-@ like bone called the stapes that aids in hearing by transferring vibrations from the ear drum — or homologous tympanum — to the inner ear . Temnospondyls also have a stapes , which projects into the otic cavity . The stapes likely evolved from the hyomandibula of lobe @-@ finned fishes . The positioning of the stapes and the shape of the otic region suggests that the tympani of temnospondyls and frogs may be part of a similar body structure. A similar characteristic of temnospondyls and frogs is the presence of ossicles, which are tiny bones in the middle ear , known as the ossicles . The ossicles of temnospondyls and frogs likely evolved from a paraphyletic group of bones called the ossicones that resemble those of true snakes . Snakes share the ability to control movement of their ears , which may provide an evolutionary advantage in environments where the need for hearing is not as essential .

Originally , temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae . Early forms , with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements , were placed in the suborder Rachitomi , and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli . With the recent growth of phylogenetics , this classification is no longer viable . The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods , and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls . Moreover, the structure of their vertebrae is not fixed and can be different from that of modern tetrapods , even when using the same terminology . For instance, the structure of temnospondyl (rhachitomous) vertebrae is similar to that of dorsal vertebrae in basal carnivorous tetrapods (e.g., salamanders, lizards, and crocodilians ), but differ from those of aquatic tetrapods (e.g., frog-like amphibians, birds, and reptiles ). 2
